VL  - 25
IS  - 1
SP  - 97
EP  - 112
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(90)90047-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393290900478
AB  - When monetary and fiscal authorities cooperate to minimize the distortionary costs of financing an exogenous stream of government expenditures, Barro's tax-smoothing model implies a long-run relationship between tax revenues and inflation. Previous empirical tests of this relationship are reinterpreted in light of recent work on cointegration and are shown to hold only when stochastic temporal variation in the excess burden of taxes and seigniorage is transitory in nature. A new test that holds in the presence of nonstationary disturbances is developed and applied. Annual U.S. data from the period 1914 to 1986 reject the revenue-smoothing hypothesis.
